        12 .

<http://connectivity-hub.com/terms/f0914a46-c1d4-445d-b5fc-cf24218fb4fe> a skos:Concept ;
    dcterms:created "2025-06-25T15:23:34.980000+00:00"^^xsd:dateTime ;
    dcterms:modified "2025-06-26T08:45:37.934000+00:00"^^xsd:dateTime ;
    skos:broader <http://connectivity-hub.com/terms/ad0f0538-f168-4c67-afce-dc9598155cde> ;
    skos:definition "The inverse of the escalating cascade, where each subsequent impact propagated in a cascade is dampened or reduced compared to the previous one. Using a similar supply chain example, fixed prices may be built-in to contracts between retailers and suppliers, hence safeguarding prices for recipient consumers but also implying that suppliers would absorb any additional costs (potentially exposing them to increased impacts) (Carter et al., 2021)."@en ;
    skos:historyNote "Carter, T.R., Benzie, M., Campiglio, E., Carlsen, H., Franzek, S., Hildén, M., Reyer, C.P.O. and West, C. (2021). A conceptual framework for cross-border impacts of climate change. Global Environmental Change, 69, https://doi.org/10.1016/j.gloenvcha.2021.102307"@en ;
    skos:inScheme <http://connectivity-hub.com/terms/> ;
    skos:prefLabel "Diminishing cascade"@en ;
    skos:related <http://connectivity-hub.com/terms/1263d9b4-76ce-4d59-82a7-94ef797b4b8f>,
        <http://connectivity-hub.com/terms/59a9d753-5ce4-489e-addb-715319eed174>,
        <http://connectivity-hub.com/terms/5a02c7e5-d036-4ba0-9a00-6ee891f9fde5>,
        <http://connectivity-hub.com/terms/9a03b4e4-0c98-4e6d-b360-da0c58ee1f3d> ;
    skos:topConceptOf <http://connectivity-hub.com/terms/> ;
    ns1:revisionNo 9 .

<http://connectivity-hub.com/terms/0ae68762-fb7d-47e2-a0c8-3ff0ef9d8155> a skos:Concept ;
    dcterms:created "2025-06-26T08:39:49.558000+00:00"^^xsd:dateTime ;
    dcterms:modified "2025-06-26T09:31:58.845000+00:00"^^xsd:dateTime ;
    skos:broader <http://connectivity-hub.com/terms/28b7c1f7-ae68-4e4a-81f1-6e66bf04fd12>,
        <http://connectivity-hub.com/terms/486d1357-c138-4fe0-969b-f5668731ca93> ;
    skos:definition """Indirect risk arises when the effects of
disasters have an impact on a broader
range of elements within a system,
including those outside the directly 
affected area, via links and connections
within the system (Arrighi et al., 2021).
As a result, loss levels grow higher with
increasing interconnectivity, particularly 
due to international trade and growing
complexity of supply chains (Hochrainer
-Stigler and Reiter, 2021)."""@en ;
    skos:historyNote """Arrighi, C., Pregnolato, M., and Castelli, F.: Indirect flood impacts and cascade risk across interdependent linear infrastructures, Nat. Hazards Earth Syst. Sci., 21, 1955–1969, https://doi.org/10.5194/nhess-21-1955-2021, 2021.

Bednar-Friedl, B., Knittel, N., Raich, J. and Adams, K.M. (2022). 'Adaptation to transboundary climate risks in trade: Investigating actors and strategies for an emerging challenge', WIRE's Climate Change, 13:e758, https://doi.org/10.1002/wcc.758 

Hochrainer-Stigler, S., Reiter, K. Risk-Layering for Indirect Effects. Int J Disaster Risk Sci 12, 770–778 (2021). https://doi.org/10.1007/s13753-021-00366-2"""@en ;
    skos:inScheme <http://connectivity-hub.com/terms/> ;
    skos:narrower <http://connectivity-hub.com/terms/1263d9b4-76ce-4d59-82a7-94ef797b4b8f> ;
    skos:prefLabel "Indirect risk"@en ;
    skos:related <http://connectivity-hub.com/terms/9a03b4e4-0c98-4e6d-b360-da0c58ee1f3d>,
        <http://connectivity-hub.com/terms/a8b34fb2-6d75-4281-a527-f1764e3bb3f2>,
        <http://connectivity-hub.com/terms/ad0f0538-f168-4c67-afce-dc9598155cde> ;
    skos:scopeNote """Indirect risks, similarly to cascading risks, invoke differences between first-order climate risks (e.g., direct climate risks, often contained within national borders) and higher-order risks (e.g., risks which are triggered elsewhere and may flow across sectors or borders). Risks conceptualised in this way may be plausibly contained within a national border, but across sectors, as the key characteristic is the hierarchical ordering of a risk, rather than the distance it flows.

Yet, while indirect risk is a broader concept and describes the general consequences of a particular event, cascading risk refers to a situation in which the initial impact triggers a further sequence of events, often across multiple systems and places. Thus, cascading risk is a particular type of indirect risk, characterised specifically by a chain reaction of repercussions (Arrighi et al., 2021)."""@en ;
    skos:topConceptOf <http://connectivity-hub.com/terms/> ;
    ns1:revisionNo 11 .

